Every stone above should be evaluated using the 8-step framework before purchase. The Ideal and Excellent cut designations narrow the field but do not substitute for depth %, L/W ratio, shoulder curvature, and video bow-tie evaluation on each individual stone.

## Final Verdict: Elongated Pear Diamond Proportions

**The single most important specification** is depth %, not L/W ratio. L/W ratio is what buyers notice first — but a stone can be in the ideal L/W range and still underperform because of a depth % outside 58–64%. Get the depth right first.

**The second most important check** is the video bow-tie evaluation. No proxy replaces it. A GIA Excellent symmetry grade, Ideal cut designation, and ideal L/W + depth combination can all be present in a stone that still crosses the Bow-Tie Threshold. Watch the video on every stone before purchasing.

**For buyers who specifically want an elongated pear diamond:** target 1.60–1.65:1 L/W, 59–63% depth, 55–62% table, GIA Excellent or Very Good symmetry and polish, and apply the shoulder curvature check before shortlisting. The [GIA 1ct D-VS1 Ideal at $3,803](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29112328?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the natural 1ct entry point — verify its proportions on the detail page and watch the video before purchase.

**For lab grown buyers:** apply the same 8-step framework to IGI and GIA certified lab pear diamonds. The [IGI 1ct D-VVS1 Ideal lab pear at $1,006](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26932733?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry point. Lab grown pear diamonds require the same proportions evaluation as natural stones — the lab origin does not change the cut geometry or the bow-tie physics.

## Expert Summary

> The most common mistake I see in pear diamond buying is treating L/W ratio as a standalone specification. Buyers fixate on achieving 1.60:1 or 1.65:1, hit the target, and then skip the depth check and the video. But an elongated pear diamond at 1.63:1 with 66% depth is going to look noticeably smaller face-up than the chart says it should, and will likely show a more pronounced bow-tie because the steep pavilion angles can't return light through the central zone. The Shoulder Crush is the other thing nobody checks — if you pull up the stone photograph and the arc from the shoulder to the wing tip has a flat spot or a pinch, that stone is going to look wrong in a setting regardless of what the numbers say. The 8-step framework I recommend takes about 10 minutes per stone. At $4,000 to $25,000 for a pear diamond engagement ring, 10 minutes per stone is the most valuable diligence you can do.
>
> — Farzana Hasan, Fine Jewelry Analyst

## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is the ideal L/W ratio for an elongated pear diamond?

The ideal length-to-width ratio for an elongated pear diamond is 1.60–1.65:1. This range delivers visible finger elongation in an engagement ring setting without the stone appearing too narrow. Below 1.50:1 is a chubby pear diamond. Above 1.70:1 is a very elongated pear that can appear narrow on most ring profiles. Calculate L/W from the listed measurements on Blue Nile's detail page: Length ÷ Width from the millimeter dimensions.

### What is a chubby pear diamond?

A chubby pear diamond is an informal term for a pear shaped diamond with a length-to-width ratio below approximately 1.48:1. The wide, full silhouette gives the stone a rounded, compact teardrop appearance rather than an elongated one. Chubby pear diamonds are not inferior — they suit east-west ring settings, wider finger profiles, and buyers who prefer a full, balanced teardrop silhouette over a narrow elongated one.

### What is the ideal depth percentage for a pear diamond?

The ideal depth percentage for a pear brilliant cut diamond is 58–64%. Below 56%, the stone shows a windowing effect where light passes through the table without reflecting. Above 66%, the stone carries excess depth that reduces face-up size without improving brilliance. Depth % is listed explicitly on every Blue Nile diamond detail page.

### What is the ideal table percentage for a pear diamond?

The ideal table percentage for a pear shaped diamond is 53–65%. This range produces the correct balance between crown height (which generates fire) and face-up area. Table % above 66% indicates a flat crown that reduces fire; below 52% indicates an excessively tall crown that reduces brilliance. Check table % on the Blue Nile stone detail page before purchasing.

### Do all pear diamonds have a bow-tie effect?

Yes. All pear diamonds have some degree of bow-tie shadow across the stone's widest midpoint. The bow-tie effect is caused by the viewer's head blocking light from certain reflection angles — it is an inherent optical characteristic of elongated brilliant cuts, not a defect. The relevant question is severity. A faint bow-tie is acceptable; a pronounced dark band across the center is not. Always watch the video on each stone's Blue Nile detail page to evaluate bow-tie severity before purchasing.

### What causes a severe bow-tie in a pear diamond?

Severe bow-tie in a pear diamond is caused by the interaction of L/W ratio, depth %, and shoulder curvature. Stones with depth below 57% (shallow pavilion) often have severe bow-ties because the pavilion angles cannot redirect light through the central zone. Very elongated stones above 1.70:1 L/W are more susceptible because the central shadow zone is geometrically larger. Poor shoulder curvature (the Shoulder Crush) amplifies bow-tie even when L/W and depth are within ideal ranges.

### What is pear diamond symmetry and why does it matter?

Symmetry for a pear diamond describes how accurately the two halves of the stone mirror each other across the stone's axis from tip to base midpoint. GIA grades symmetry as Excellent, Very Good, Good, Fair, or Poor. A pear diamond with Excellent symmetry has precisely matched shoulders, aligned wing tips, and a tip that sits on the stone's central axis. Poor symmetry means visible asymmetry in the silhouette and an off-axis tip that does not sit correctly in a V-prong setting. Minimum recommended symmetry: Very Good. Excellent is preferred.

### What does GIA Excellent symmetry mean for a pear diamond?

GIA Excellent symmetry for a pear diamond means the stone's outline is geometrically accurate — both shoulders match, the tip aligns with the central axis, and the wing tips are at equal heights. However, GIA Excellent symmetry does not guarantee good light performance. A GIA Excellent symmetry pear diamond can still have severe bow-tie, poor shoulder curvature, or suboptimal depth %. The symmetry grade evaluates geometric accuracy, not optical performance.

### Is a pear brilliant cut the same as a pear diamond?

Yes. Pear brilliant cut, pear shaped diamond, pear diamond, and teardrop diamond all describe the same modified brilliant cut. "Pear brilliant" is the formal gemological term. "Teardrop diamond" is informal. When searching Blue Nile or any major retailer, use "pear" — "teardrop" is not a standard inventory category filter.

### What is the pear diamond vs teardrop shape difference?

There is no difference. A teardrop diamond and a pear diamond are the same shape. Teardrop is a colloquial consumer term based on the shape's resemblance to a falling water droplet. Gemologically, the cut is classified as pear brilliant. All GIA and IGI certificates identify this shape as "Pear."

### How do I evaluate pear diamond cut quality if GIA doesn't give a cut grade?

GIA does not issue overall cut grades for pear shaped diamonds the way it does for round brilliants. Evaluate pear diamond cut quality using this 8-step framework: (1) filter for Ideal or Excellent cut on Blue Nile; (2) check L/W ratio; (3) check depth % (target 58–64%); (4) check table % (target 53–65%); (5) check symmetry and polish (Very Good minimum); (6) evaluate shoulder curvature from the outline photograph; (7) watch the video for bow-tie severity; (8) check tip alignment in the video. No single specification substitutes for this full framework.

### What is the best pear shaped diamond cut to look for?

For a pear shaped diamond cut, filter Blue Nile for Ideal or Excellent cut designation, then apply the full proportions framework: L/W ratio in your target range, depth % 58–64%, table % 53–65%, GIA Excellent or Very Good symmetry and polish, smooth shoulder curvature, and acceptable bow-tie in the video. The cut grade is a starting filter, not a conclusion.

### How does depth percentage affect pear diamond face-up size?

A pear diamond at 60% depth will appear larger face-up at a given carat weight than the same carat stone at 65% depth. This is because more depth means more stone mass is hidden below the girdle. At equivalent carat weights, stones in the 58–62% depth range deliver more face-up millimeters than stones at 63–66%. The trade-off is stability — too shallow (below 57%) and the stone shows windowing and is more fragile at the point.

